        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In addition to our primary goal for continuum, we plan to observe three molecular lines in parallel. Our current set up will only increase about 13 min of observing time (54 min in total) but enables us to obtain more dynamical or chemical informations. This is much more efficient than using four continuum windows.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We attempt to resolve the binary system IRAS 16253 with the requested angular resolution of 0.1 arcsec (12.5 AU at 125 pc in Ophiuchus molecular cloud). If we adopt an orbital period of 3000 yr and the binary separation of 12.5 AU, we could derived a mass of the central stars as 0.0002 Msun.
However, the low mass protostars are unlikely to drive the outflow with mass of 0.0014 Msun obtained from the single dish CO (2-1) and (6-5) data, if we consider a mass loss rate to mass accretion rate of 0.2-0.5. Therefore, we suggest that the binary separation is larger than 0.1 arcsec.
On the other hand, we chose the large scale of 5 arcsec because the source size is 4.6" x 5.0" in FWHM based on the Gaussian fitting to the SMA continuum image.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We discuss the sensitivity required for detecting the companion in IRAS 16253 based on our SMA observations at 224GHz. We speculate the peak intensity is 16 mJy/beam toward the infrared object is contributed by the primary star and its companion, and both are point-like sources at the requested angular resolution 0.1" (12.5 AU). We use a conservative assumption that the companion only contributes 1/20 of the peak flux (16/20 = 0.8 mJy mJy/beam). We requested 0.9 hours of observing time, which will enable to achive a rms noise level of 0.08 mJy and to detecte the companion with a S/N ratio of 10.
The C18O peak intensity in our SMA obserations is ~1 Jy/beam at a spectral resolution of 0.28 km/s. Our requested observations will therefore achieve a S/N ratio of 77 if the SMA peak intensity contributed by a point source.
Our requested observing time </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
