    <prp:abstract>The formation mechanism(s) of brown dwarfs (BDs, M&lt;0.08 Msun) has been a longstanding problem. Resolving it requires studying their properties during the embedded phase (proto-BDs). We aim to identify a potential proto-BD, IRAS16253-2429. Our SMA CO(2-1) observations revealed two protostellar outflows, suggesting IRAS16253 is a binary system. The low mass of parent core (&lt;0.5 Msun) implies that the central objects may accrete only ~0.05 Msun of material in the future. As a result, IRAS16253 is likely to form one or two BDs depending on the current masses and the future accretion process. The CO outflows show periodic line-of-sight velocity variations along the outflow axes, and we deduce an orbital period of 3000 yr. With Kepler's third law, the current total mass of the central stars can be inferred from this orbital period as a function of the binary separation. If the binary separation is &lt; 1, IRAS16253 should contain at least one proto-BD. Our proposed observation will resolve and probe the dynamics of the binary in IRAS16253.  This will be the first dynamical identification of a proto-BD system, allowing us to gain insight into the formation of the lowest-mass binary systems.</prp:abstract>
